<DOC><DOCNO> AP891231-0015 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-31-89 1120EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-HotelBombing     12-31 0214</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Hotel Bombing,0219</SECOND><HEAD>Hotel Destroyed in Bombing, Organized Crime Suspected</HEAD><DATELINE>AJACCIO, Corsica (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   An explosion destroyed a closed resorthotel, and police said Sunday that organized crime figures wereprobably responsible. Five months ago, the hotel manager's son wasgunned down in the street.   No injuries were reported in the blast Saturday night at the URiposo hotel in Sagone on Corsica's western coast, policeinvestigators said.   Whoever set the blast used bottles of gas and 220 pounds ofunidentified explosives that smashed the foundation of the 22-room,three-story hotel, hurled rubble across the street and lit up thenight sky, police said.   The hotel was for sale and had been closed since the end of thesummer.   On Aug. 7, Jean Renouard, the son of the hotel manager, was shotto death while sitting in his car.   The previous manager, Jean Dupuis, was killed in a similarfashion in 1985. Dupuis had been involved with a local citizens'law enforcement organization.   Police did not explain why organized crime figures would havetargeted the hotel or its staff.   Organized crime in Corsica, a poor region whose main industriesare fishing and tourism, has traditionally been based onkidnapping, extortion and murder. In recent years gangsters haveincreasingly turned their attention to drugs.</TEXT></DOC>